abstract_summ: Government and professional videos contained only factual information and had higher CSS than consumer videos (mean difference (MD) 2.21, 95% CI 0.10 to 4.32, p=0.037); mDISCERN scores than consumer videos (MD 2.46, 95% CI 0.50 to 4.42, p=0.008), internet news videos (MD 2.20, 95% CI 0.19 to 4.21, p=0.027) and entertainment news videos (MD 2.57, 95% CI 0.66 to 4.49, p=0.004); and mJAMA scores than entertainment news videos (MD 1.21, 95% CI 0.07 to 2.36, p=0.033) and consumer videos (MD 1.27, 95% CI 0.10 to 2.44, p=0.028).Independent users were more likely to post misleading videos than useful videos (60.0% vs 21.5%, P = 0.009).News agencies were more likely to post useful videos than misleading videos (72.2% vs 40.0%, P = 0.039).Average view counts, view ratios, and VPIs of misleading videos are higher than the useful videos.Results: The mean DISCERN score of Turkish videos is similar to English videos (2.55 and 2.43 respectively).
